3. silvam . . . sacram: cf. 9. 9, lacos ac nemora consecrant. —auguriis patrum et prisca formidine sacram: these words form a complete hexameter. Tacitus doubtless slipped into the rhythm unconsciously; similar lapses —for so ancient stylists considered them— occur semi-occasionally elsewhere in Latin prose writers. The first clause in Livy⁷s preface to his history forms part of a hexameter and in Book 22. 50 the words haec ubi dicta dedit, strinyit yladium cuneoquesacto per medios are a hexam- eter and a half. The diction here has a poetic color, com- parable to Vergil, Aeneid 7.172, (tectum) horrendum silvis et reliqione parentum, and this fact rendered it easy for Tacitus to glide into a rhythmic cadence. 7. nisi vinculo ligatus: the interpretation given by Tacitus of the inner significance of this usage is correct. Cords and bonds figure not infrequently in ritual and religion as symbols of the subjection of a devotee to a deity. The fillet used in Greek and Roman worship was in origin a badge of devotion and consecration to a higher power.
